data: At one time in the early 1880s, a thousand people lived in this mining camp. It has been a ghost town since the last resident died in 1939.
At the core of this expanded house is one of the few remaining original miner's cabins in the city, and the only one from prior to 1885 made of hand-hewn logs.
The unusual projecting northeast corner bay on this 1888 frame Queen Anne miner's house is a unique local design not found in pattern books or other Queen Anne homes in Aspen.
Remnants of an original 1885 log cabin were discovered during a mid-20th-century renovation of this house expanded by a local mine owner.

This 1891 sandstone commercial building is the only one remaining financed by David Hyman, an early investor in Aspen. It has been used as a gas station and car dealership since then; today it is home to the upscale boutiques that give it and the neighboring Collins Block the nickname "Glitter Gulch".
Never significantly altered, this 1887 surviving miner's cabin is considered one of the best remaining in the city. It is now a Japanese restaurant.
This ornate 1888 commercial building is the second-oldest brick one in the city. It was later a ski shop, and is now one of Aspen's most valuable properties.
This 1892 saloon, long known as "The Red Onion" is Aspen's oldest operating restaurant.
Details of this Swiss Chalet style residence built in 1901 for the Osgood estate serve both aesthetic and functional purposes.
This 1901 cottage is an intact, surviving example of the many that Osgood built for workers in Redstone.
State Highway 133 and Chair Mountain Stables Rd.
An 1890 West End Queen Anne later home to the Aspen Music Festival cofounder, it is only house in that style in the city with an attached tower.

Later called the "Christmas tree house", it was built by an early mine owner in 1890. Later it was occupied by the Elisha family, owners of Hotel Jerome in early 20th century. Today it is considered one of the city's finest Queen Annes.

The only silver mine still operating in Aspen was, in its day, responsible for one-fifth of the country's silver production. Largest silver nugget ever, weighing more than a ton, was mined here in 1890s.
Established in 1880 to bury an early pioneer, it became the final resting place of many of Aspen's working-class residents through the Depression.
